h masculine orientation, however, neither Judaism nor Christianity lacks elaboration on the female principle. When an ancient author chooses female imagery in order to make his message more emphatic, the female body as such forms an integral part of their metaphors. The contributions in this volume explore this phenomenon within the literature of early Judaism, and within its broad environments.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBible. New TestamentxCriticism, interpretation, etcxCongresses. 0aBible. Old TestamentxCriticism, interpretation, etcxCongesses. 0aHuman body in the BiblevCongresses. 0aHuman body in the BiblexCongresses. 0aMiddle Eastern literaturexHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aMiddle Eastern literaturexHistory and criticismxCongresses. 0aWomen in the BiblevCongresses. 0aWomen in the BiblexCongresses. 4aFrühes Christentum. 4aFrühes Judentum. 4aGenderrollen. 4aKonzepte von Weiblichkeit. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / Women's Issues.2bisacsh  aEarly Christianity.  aEarly Judaism.  afemininity.  agender.1 aBalla, Ibolya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Suzanne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsztári, Réka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFröhlich, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoff, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHieke, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKőszeghy, Miklós, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParlagi, Gáspár, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchöpflin, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel